### Solution 1: greedy, bitmasking

As soon as we see a character the second time we need to start a new partition.

```
    static int partitionString(const string& s) {
        int ans = 1;
        int seen = 0;
        for (char ch : s) {
            const int mask = 1 << (ch - 'a');
            if (seen & mask) {
                ++ans;
                seen = 0;
            }
            seen |= mask;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

**EDIT**: I could achieve a good speed up by using bitmasking (https://leetcode.com/submissions/detail/927759816/) instead of substration (disclaimer the runtimes are not very predictable), i.e.:
```
            const int mask = 1 << (ch & 31);
```

It's intersting to see that clang produces quite different code for this minor change: https://godbolt.org/z/qK6haEjs9

**Complexity Analysis**
  * Time Complexity: O(n), with n = size(s). We are looking at each character of the input exactly once.
  * Space Complexity: O(1)

