# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
# 3RD ONE LINER
```C++ []
const static auto initialize = [] { std::ios::sync_with_stdio(false); std::cin.tie(nullptr); std::cout.tie(nullptr); return nullptr; }();

class Solution
{
public:
	int partitionString(std::string const& s)
	{
		return std::accumulate(std::cbegin(s), std::cend(s), 1,
			[observed = std::array<int, 26>{0}](auto count, auto c) mutable
			{
				if (observed[c - 'a'] == count) { ++count; }
				return observed[c - 'a'] = count;
			});
	}
};
```
# dry run 
•	For the input string "abacaba", the function will iterate through each character in the string and keep track of the characters seen so far using a bit mask.
•	Initially, the bit mask is 0 and the count is 1.
•	For the first character 'a', the bit mask is updated to 1 (1<<'a') and the count remains 1.
•	For the second character 'b', the bit mask is updated to 3 (1<<'a' | 1<<'b') and the count remains 1.
•	For the third character 'a', the bit mask is updated to 2 (1<<'b') and the count remains 1.
•	For the fourth character 'c', the bit mask is updated to 10 (1<<'b' | 1<<'c') and the count remains 1.
•	For the fifth character 'a', the bit mask is updated to 8 (1<<'c') and the count remains 1.
•	For the sixth character 'b', the bit mask is updated to 24 (1<<'a' | 1<<'c' | 1<<'b') and the count remains 1.
•	For the seventh character 'a', the bit mask is updated to 16 (1<<'a' | 1<<'c') and the count is incremented to 2 because the bit mask already contains the character 'a'.
•	The final count is 4, which is the minimum number of substrings needed to partition the string.



