## Intuition / approach
Observe that no letters can be in more than one substring
Therefore, we can use a greedy approach:
-- Starting from the beginning of the string, store which letters appear for each index
-- If an index's letter already exists, increment the result and reset the current letters (starting a new substring)

## Code

Time: $$O(n)$$
Space: $$O(1)$$

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int partitionString(string str) {
        bool found[26]{};
        int res = 1;
        for (char c: str) {
            if (found[c-'a']) {
                // Because a duplicate appeared, we must begin a new substring
                ++res;
                memset(found, 0, sizeof found);
            }
            found[c-'a'] = true;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
Resetting the `found` array is pretty fast, but there are still 26 values to reset.
By storing the current level of the `found` array using an int, we can "reset" the found array by simply increasing the level.
Fortunately, we already have a variable to do that (the result variable)
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int partitionString(string str) {
        int found[26]{};
        int res = 1;
        for (char c: str) {
            if (found[c-'a'] == res) {
                // Because a duplicate appeared, we must begin a new substring
                ++res;  // This will also "reset" the array
            }
            found[c-'a'] = res;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
Or, use a bitwise solution to further increase the speed
Note that this only works because we have 26 keys (26 <= 32)
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int partitionString(string str) {
        int res = 1, found = 0;
        for (char c: str) {
            if (found & 1<<c-'a') {
                ++res;
                found = 0;
            }
            found |= 1<<c-'a';
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
