# Approach
To solve this problem, we can use a greedy approach. We start with the first character and keep adding characters to a substring as long as each new character is unique. Once we encounter a character that is already present in the substring, we create a new substring starting with that character. We repeat this process until we reach the end of the string.
We use an unordered_set to keep track of the characters in the current substring. If we encounter a character that is already in the set, we increment the count and clear the set to start a new substring. We add 1 to the count at the end to account for the last substring that may not have been counted yet.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n), where n is the length of the input string

- Space complexity:
O(k), where k is the number of unique characters in the input string.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int partitionString(string s) {
        int n = s.length();
        unordered_set<char> seen;
        int count = 0;
        int i = 0;
        while (i < n) {
            char c = s[i];
            if (seen.count(c) == 0) {
                seen.insert(c);
                i++;
            } else {
                count++;
                seen.clear();
            }
        }
        count++; 
        return count;
    }
};

```

